{\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \qc{\b Abstract}\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \li1024\ri1024\fi0 The study of Sri Lanka Malay has focussed on the genesis scenario, where theories of creolization ({Smith et\~al.} 2004, {Smith & Paauw} 2006) with a dominant role of Tamil compete with theories of convergence ({Bakker} 2006, {Ansaldo} 2008) which allow for a more important role for Sinhala. This paper assesses and reevaluates the empirical data brought forward by both sides and contributes more empirical data on parallels with Sinhala. These parallels are partly due to substrate reinforcement ({Siegel} 1998) of marginal structures found in Malay varieties, partly they are clear calques on Sinhala patterns. Some structures must be analysed as the result of Early Sinhala Influence during the colonial period, while for others, a later development following socio-political changes after independence is possible (Late Sinhala Influence). The paper argues that SLM changes towards Sinhala at both periods can be seen as a kind of metatypy comparable to other language contact settings in Eurasia and Papua. \par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb360 \fi0 {\s3\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_retro}1{\*\bkmkend BMex_retro}  Introduction\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Sri Lanka Malay is a contact variety of Malay which has undergone heavy grammatical restructuring towards Indian typology ({Adelaar} 1991, {Paauw} 2004, {Smith et\~al.} 2004, {Smith & Paauw} 2006, {Slomanson} 2006, {Bakker} 2006, {Ansaldo} 2008, {Nordhoff} 2009). This is true for all domains of grammar, from phonology to discourse. Among the features which show that Sri Lanka Malay has become a member of the Indian sprachbund, we find phonemic retroflexes as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_retro \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1}}}), infinitives as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_inf \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1}}}), conjunctive participles as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_cp \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1}}}), and preposed relative clauses as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_relc \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1}}}), to name but a few of the various instances from different domains of grammar.\par
