{\*\footnote \pard\plain\s246\f13\fs20 {\up16\chftn}\i Dia \i0 is disyllabic. }
 This phonological account finds support from additional data in {Nordhoff} (2009:225), where we find the forms \i dedang\i0 , \lquote 3s.{\scaps impolite.dative}\rquote  and \i diyanang\i0 , \lquote 3s.{\scaps polite.dative}\rquote . Both forms are third person, but one is monosyllabic (\i de \i0 ) while the other one is disyllabic (\i diya\i0 ). As predicted by the phonological analysis, the monosyllabic pronoun takes \i -dang \i0 and the disyllabic one, \i -nang\i0 . One could try to save the animacy account and argue that impolite forms are higher on the Animacy Hierarchy than polite forms but this clearly stretches this particular hierarchy beyond its capacities, besides being unintuitive in the first place.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Even if we accept the animacy account for the sake of discussion, we have to explain how this distinction was brought about by Sinhala influence. {Ansaldo} (2008:31) argues that \ldblquote unlike Tamil, the Sinhala system has a natural gender in which the main distinction is between Animate and Inanimate. Inanimate nouns can take four cases [...], while Animate nouns have two additional cases [...]. The animacy effect noted in the SLM pronouns could have developed under influence of a more pervasive animacy feature found in Sinhala.\rdblquote  Sinhala thus does not have the difference in case allomorphs as argued for SLM. Rather, it has animacy effects in the number of cases available to different lexemes. The transfer can thus not be a direct influence from Sinhala, but must take some more intricate path involving \ldblquote transfer of semantic features without corresponding syntactic categories\rdblquote  ({Ansaldo} 2008:31). If we accept this particular possibility, it is clear that Tamil features could also be at the origin of the SLM distinction. Tamil has animacy distinctions in verbal agreement and number marking,{\up16\chftn}
{\*\footnote \pard\plain\s246\f13\fs20 {\up16\chftn}Sinhala furthermore also has distinctions along the lines of animacy in plural formation ({Nitz & Nordhoff} 2010) and selection of existential verbs. }
 which could have made use of the same mechanism as proposed for Sinhala by Ansaldo. To sum up, the animacy analysis of the pronominal paradigm is problematic to begin with, but even if we accept it, a clear case for Sinhala influence rather than Tamil influence cannot be made.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s5\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs24 1.3.6  Semantics of the instrumental case marker\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Another domain of Sinhala influence argued by {Ansaldo} (2008:32,35) is the conflation of instrumental and ablative, both marked by \i -riNG{} \i0 in the Kirinda dialect. This is what he finds in Sinhala, but crucially not in Tamil, were these two cases are distinguished. Ansaldo does not give the actual case forms, but I take the Sinhala forms to be \i -ing \i0 ([-anim]), \i -geng \i0 ([+anim]) for ablative/instrumental and the Tamil forms \i -aale \i0 for the instrumental and \i -(i)runtu \i0 for the ablative.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 According to Ansaldo, SLM has a conflation of ablative and instrumental like Sinhala, and unlike Tamil. For this, a clear analysis of the Sinhala and the Tamil systems based on common criteria is necessary. It happens that Sinhala studies and Tamil studies use different definitions of case. This leads to the disappearing of two cases from the Sinhala paradigms found in the literature, which would have been there if the Tamil standards had been applied. An equivalence of the cases of interest here is given in Table {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMtab_cases \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{5}}}.\par
