}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 We see that while Tamil has an instrumental suffix (\i -aale\i0 ), and SLM has an instrumental enclitic postposition (\i =dering\i0 , Ansaldo\rquote s\i -riNG\i0 ). Sinhala has a circumlocution with the free word \i atiNG\i0 , \lquote with the hand\rquote , which is paradigmatic, but not phonologically integrated, leading to the exclusion from case paradigms in the literature.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The same is true of the form \i iUNDalaa\i0 , which is the conjunctive participle of the animate existential \i innavaa\i0 . In Sinhala studies, this form is regarded as an independent word and not analyzed as forming part of the case paradigm. The Tamil form \i iruntu\i0 , originally also the conjunctive participle of the existential (\i iru\i0 ), on the other hand, is analyzed as a case suffix and found in the ablative cell of paradigms by Tamil scholars. As for SLM, the conjunctive participle of the animate existential, \i as\u224?duuduk\i0 , is normally not seen as a case marker, but rather as a free word as in Sinhala. It is clear, however, that all three languages have a clear ablative marking based on the very same process, the grammaticalization of the conjunctive participle of the existential. This is phonologically more integrated into the host word in Tamil, in line with the overall structure of this language, than in Sinhala or SLM, but the semantics in what concerns thematic role expressed are the same.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The choice of the ablative marker is obligatory in Tamil, but optional in Sinhala and SLM, where the instrumental marker can be used instead. The parallels between Sinhala and SLM are thus closer here. Furthermore, the original distinction between the old Malay ablative preposition \i dari \i0 and the instrumental preposition \i pake \i0 has been lost in Sri Lanka Malay, where only \i dering\i0 , the reflex of \i dari\i0 , remained. This conflation cannot be due to Tamil influence since Tamil keeps its instrumental and its ablative distinct at all times. It must be due to Sinhala influence, where \i -geng \i0 or \i -ing \i0 can be used for both meanings. On the other hand, there is a difference in animacy for the Sinhala instrumental forms not found in SLM. This suggest less influence from Sinhala here. To sum up, the conflation of instrumental and ablative posited for Sinhala and SLM is more involved than previously assumed, but a case for Sinhala influence to the exclusion of Tamil can still be made.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 1.4  Summary of previous claims\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Taking a look at what has been said above about the mainly nominal categories of number, case, and definiteness, an muddled picture emerges. Accusative seems to be closer to Tamil, while the indefiniteness marker and the conflation of ablative and instrumental point towards influence from Sinhala ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMtab_summaryscreening \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{6}}}). The other features discussed in the literature had to be discarded because retention cannot be ruled out (number marking), the scenario suggested would trigger other changes than the ones observed (dental stops) or the analysis of SLM data was problematic (animacy in pronouns). It is clear that more empirical data is needed. This will be addressed in the next section.\par
