}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb360 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_exist_slm_bats}2.4{\*\bkmkend BMex_exist_slm_bats}  Existentials\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Malay varieties generally have only one existential marker, \i ada\i0 . This marker is also found in SLM, where it surfaces as \i aada\i0 . Form and semantics of this marker are clearly inherited. Compare Indonesian \i rumah ada\i0 , \lquote There are houses\rquote  with SLM \i ruuma aada\i0 , \lquote id.\rquote \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 In distinction to Indonesian, Sinhala and Tamil both have two existential markers, but their semantics are different. In Sinhala, the distinguishing parameter is clearly animacy ({Karunatillake} 2004:12). Existence of animate referents is expressed by \i innavaa\i0 , while existence of inanimate referents is expressed by \i tiyenavaa\i0 . Swapping the existentials leads to ungrammaticality, as the following example shows.\par
()()\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 mee iskolee sinhala panti tunak tiyenavaa/*innavaa {\scaps Sinhala} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 this school.{\scaps loc} Sinhala classes three exist.{\scaps inanim}/exist.{\scaps anim} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote There are three Sinhala classes in this school.\rquote  a.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 langkaava rilaw huUNGak *tiyenavaa/innavaa {\scaps Sinhala} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Sri{ }Lanka monkeys many exist.{\scaps inanim}/exist.{\scaps anim} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote There are many (macaque) monkeys in Sri Lanka.\rquote  ({Gair} 2003:790) \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Such a clear semantic distinction is not found in Tamil. There, \i iru \i0 is the default marker. It is occasionally substituted by \i undu\i0 , but the conditioning semantic parameters are less clear than in Sinhala and in no case identical to what we find in the latter language.{\up16\chftn}
