{\*\footnote \pard\plain\s246\f13\fs20 {\up16\chftn}Note that another reflex of \i kena \i0 retains the adversative reading, namely \i k\u236?nna\i0 . See {Nordhoff} (2009:187-192) for a discussion of this construction.}
 Still, it is clear that the segmental material for the SLM construction was provided by \i kena\i0 . The meaning however is closer to what is expressed by \i ter- \i0 and \i ke- \i0 in varieties of Malay. The following list sums up the semantics of these prefixes in different varieties of Malay:\par
{\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 1.\tab Manado: unexpected, involuntary ({Stoel} 2005:22) \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 2.\tab Ambon: sudden, unintentional, accidental ({van Minde} 1997:99) \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 3.\tab all Eastern Malay varieties: unintentional, accidental, unexpected ({Paauw} 2008:237) \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 4.\tab Colloquial Jakarta Indonesian: unintended, unexpected, agentless, involuntary, sudden ({Sneddon} 2006) \par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Adversativity is not implied here, although it can of course combine quite well with the meanings given above. This is the same as with SLM \i k\u224?n\u224?- \i0 above. It thus appears that SLM \i k\u224?n\u224?- \i0 is a recombination of the segmental form of \i kena \i0 and the semantics of \i ter-/ke-\i0 forms which are otherwise absent from SLM.{\up16\chftn}
{\*\footnote \pard\plain\s246\f13\fs20 {\up16\chftn}There are some fossilized forms like \i th\u224?rthaava/*thaava\i0 , \lquote laugh\rquote  which are not analysable synchronically.}
 Where Sinhala influence kicks in is in the dative marking of the involuntary agent. This cannot be of Malay origin since Malay does not have case marking at all. It cannot be Tamil either since Tamil does not possess such a kind of derivational device.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_subj_tam_dat_exp}2.6{\*\bkmkend BMex_subj_tam_dat_exp}  Non-nominative subjects\par
