\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_form_pref_ara_sim}2.7{\*\bkmkend BMex_form_pref_ara_sim}  Semantics of the non-past form\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Sinhala, Tamil and SLM all have grammaticalized tense. Malay varieties on the other hand usually have aspect as a more important parameter, and the markers are morphologically less integrated than in the Lankan languages. In this section, I will focus on the present tense form in Sri Lanka Malay, encoded by the prefix \i ar\u224?-\i0 . This marker derives from Malay \i ada\i0 , which, among other things, encodes progressive aspect in the relevant varieties ({Adelaar} 1991). In Sri Lanka Malay, it is used to refer to the present and to the future. So, \i karang ar\u224?-nyaanyi \i0 means \lquote I am singing now\rquote  and \i beesona ar\u224?-nyaanyi \i0 means \lquote I will sing tomorrow\rquote . The time reference is clearly indicated by the adverbs \i karang\i0 , \lquote now\rquote  and \i beesona\i0 , \lquote tomorrow\rquote , but \i ar\u224?- \i0 is compatible with both. The same flexibility is true of the Sinhala present tense form in \i -navaa \i0 and the Tamil present tense form in \i (kki)TEXTIPA{TEXTSUBBAR{r}}{}\i0 , the latter with some morphological complications. This does not seem spectacular up to here. The interesting point is the possibility to use the present tense form in subordinates with past reference as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_form_pref_ara_sim \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.7}}}).\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {}{ () Blaakang=jo incayang an\u224?-kuthumung [moonyeth pada ... pohong atthas=ka {\b ar\u224?-maayeng}] {\scaps SLM} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 after={\scaps emph} {\scaps 3s.polite} {\scaps past}-see monkey {\scaps pl} ... tree top={\scaps loc} {\scaps simult}-play \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote Then only he saw that the monkeys were playing on the top of the trees.\rquote  (K070000wrt01) \par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The reference time is past tense, since the action already happened. This is why the verb \i kuthumung\i0 , \lquote to see\rquote {} is marked for past tense with the prefix \i an\u224?-\i0 . The complement of this verb is an embedded clause. This clause inherits the reference time from the matrix clause, as it were. In the embedded clause, then, the only thing which is indicated is that the event of the monkeys playing was simultaneous to the man looking at them (rather than anterior or posterior). This simultaneity of the event expressed in the embedded clause with the event expressed in the matrix clause is expressed by \i ar\u224?-\i0 .\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 This is possible in the same contexts where English would use the \i -ing\i0 -form, as in \i I saw you dancing, I heard you crying, I felt you coming \i0 etc. The extension of a present tense form to a participle like form in the past is surprising. It suddenly makes more sense when we consider that the Sinhala form in \i -navaa \i0 actually started out as a non-finite form ({Geiger} 1938:163) and only later acquired the present tense reading it has today, supplanting the older finite present tense forms. Vestigial participial uses of the \i -navaa\i0 -form are still found in Sinhala ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_simult_sinh_thief \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.7}}}) ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_simult_sinh_song \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.7}}}).\par
