\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Siri thief road-{\scaps loc} run-{\scaps nonpast} see{{\\}}{\scaps past}\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote Siri saw the thief running on the road.\rquote  ({Gair} 2003:806) \par
(){\*\bkmkstart BMex_simult_sinh_song}{\*\bkmkend BMex_simult_sinh_song}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 amma=TZ{}a maalini sindu kiy-anaava \'e6{}huna {\scaps Sinhala} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 mother={\scaps dat} Malini song say-{\scaps nonpast} hear{{\\}}{\scaps past} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote Mother heard Malini singing songs.\rquote ({Gair} 2003:806) \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 The semantics of the \i -navaa\i0 -form and the \i ar\u224?\i0 -form are thus closely parallel. Both can be used for present and future. Additionally, they can be used in subordinate clauses in the past. While the \i navaa\i0 -form has changed from an erstwhile participle to a present/future form, SLM \i ar\u224?- \i0 is partly on the opposite direction and acquiring participle uses. This extension of the present tense form in the domain of subordinates finds clear role models in Sinhala, but could not possibly be explained by Tamil influence.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 One could of course argue that the use of \i ar\u224?- \i0 in progressive contexts as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_form_pref_ara_sim \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.7}}}) is a retention of the old Malay use of \i ada \i0 to denote progressive ({Adelaar} 1991). But this account falls short of explaining why the use of SLM \i ar\u224?- \i0 is only possible in \i subordinate \i0 contexts, and not in main clauses. \lquote The monkeys were playing on top of the trees\rquote  in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_form_pref_ara_sim \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.7}}}) must be marked with a past-tense prefix unless it is found in a complement clause. This restriction to subordinate clauses is not found in the relevant Malay varieties, where \i ada \i0 can be found in main clauses with past tense reference. An example of this is given in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_simult_malay \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.7}}}).\par
