}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 In this example, the case marker attaches directly to the finite verb form, leading to the curious situation that the same lexeme receives verbal marking for non-past and nominal marking for dative, without any kind of mediating derivation ( {Gair} 1991). The same is also what we find in SLM. There, finite verbs like \i as\u224?\-dhaa\-thang \i0 can immediately be marked for case without further measures being taken.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {}{ (){\*\bkmkstart BMex_nmlz_slm}{\*\bkmkend BMex_nmlz_slm} suda butthul suuka {\b as\u224?}-dhaathang-{{{\f6\'C6}}}={\b nang} {\scaps SLM} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 thus very like {\scaps cp}-come(-{\scaps nmlzr})={\scaps dat} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote So I very much liked that you came.\rquote  ({Nordhoff} 2009:327) \par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Malay varieties in general do not have case marking, so that this feature cannot directly be traced to them. However, they allow the use of prepositions with argument clauses without overt nominalization. Example ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_nmlz_ind_np \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.8}}}) shows the preposition \i untuk\i0 , \lquote for\rquote  governing an NP, while in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_nmlz_ind_cls \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.8}}}), the very same preposition governs a clause, which shows no signs of nominalization (see {Gil} (forthcoming:(11,12)) for a similar argumentation). What is more, the non-nominal status of the root \i libat\i0 , \lquote involve\rquote  is highlighted by the prefix \i me- \i0 and the applicative \i -kan\i0 , which are two of the most salient morphological signs for the verbal nature of the predicate discussed in the literature. Furthermore, \i melibatkan \i0 takes the verbal negator \i tidak \i0 rather than the nominal negator \i bukan\i0 . Note that while \i for \i0 is used in both English translations, in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_nmlz_ind_cls \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.8}}}) the verb is derived with \i -ing \i0 in order to allow the clause to be treated as an NP in this context. \par
